abstract: A Brooklyn social worker and civic leader who was colorblind to race, she could deliver votes and was courted by political candidates.
snippet: A Brooklyn social worker and civic leader who was colorblind to race, she could deliver votes and was courted by political candidates.
lead_paragraph: Mary Sansone, a gutsy Brooklyn social worker who created a robust community service organization that bridged racial and ethnic barriers, defied the Mafia and befriended supportive politicians, died on Monday in Brooklyn. She was 101.

abstract: Big banks, private equity firms and national retailers that have vowed to operate with a social conscience could band together to turn Remington into the model of a modern gun company.
snippet: Big banks, private equity firms and national retailers that have vowed to operate with a social conscience could band together to turn Remington into the model of a modern gun company.
lead_paragraph: Remington Outdoor, one of the country’s oldest and largest gun makers, is getting ready to emerge from bankruptcy.

abstract: Eradicating the artery-clogging oils from the food supply could save millions of lives, especially in developing countries, the global health agency said.
snippet: Eradicating the artery-clogging oils from the food supply could save millions of lives, especially in developing countries, the global health agency said.
lead_paragraph: The World Health Organization on Monday announced a sweeping plan that urges governments around the globe to eliminate the use of trans fats, the industrially produced edible oil that gave birth to margarine, Crisco and other artery-clogging products that have been linked to millions of premature deaths.

abstract: The city broke up big failing schools to improve academics, but at the small schools that replaced them, fielding a robust music program is a challenge.
snippet: The city broke up big failing schools to improve academics, but at the small schools that replaced them, fielding a robust music program is a challenge.
lead_paragraph: When Carmen Laboy taught music at Christopher Columbus High School in the Bronx, beginning in 1985, there were three concert bands. The pep band blasted “Malagueña” and Sousa marches on the sidelines at basketball games, and floated down Morris Park Avenue during the Columbus Day parade. The jazz band entertained crowds at the Ninth Avenue Food Festival, and even warmed the room at a Citizens Budget Commission awards dinner at the Waldorf Astoria.

abstract: The police explanation that more black and Hispanic people are arrested on marijuana charges because complaints are high in their neighborhoods doesn’t hold up to scrutiny.
snippet: The police explanation that more black and Hispanic people are arrested on marijuana charges because complaints are high in their neighborhoods doesn’t hold up to scrutiny.
lead_paragraph: They sit in courtroom pews, almost all of them young black men, waiting their turn before a New York City judge to face a charge that no longer exists in some states: possessing marijuana. They tell of smoking in a housing project hallway, or of being in a car with a friend who was smoking, or of lighting up a Black & Mild cigar the police mistake for a blunt.

lead_paragraph: Mya Lynn Thompson and Keith Bryant Doelling  met in September 2007 during their first week at college at a Harvard Black Students Association meeting. As the group flocked to a nearby Starbucks, they chatted briefly but long enough for Ms. Thompson to think to herself, “This guy from California is way too nice for the East Coast.”
